PREFACE.

AT a time when the study of the early Latin poets

has been resuscitated by the brilliant labours of

G. Hermann, F. Ritsehl, A. Fleckeisen and others, the comedies of Terence have not received sufficient attention in England, only two editions of importance having appeared during the last century. Mr Wagner’s edition is very suggestive, but he apparently hurried through

the work, for traces of carelessness are not wanting. Above all, both his edition and that of Mr Parry were written at a time when it was difficult to obtain the exact readings of the Bembine codex, and their text has suffered accordingly.
